rful images of themselves as ambitious, independent, and sexually expressive “New Women.” Female Spectacle reveals the theater to have been a powerful new source of cultural authority and visibility for women. Ironically, theater also provided an arena in which producers and audiences projected the uncertainties and hostilities that accompanied changing gender relations. From Bernhardt’s modern methods of self-promotion to Emma Goldman’s political theatrics, from the female mimics and Salome dancers to the upwardly striving chorus girl, Susan Glenn shows us how and why theater mattered to women and argues for its pivotal role in the emergence of modern feminism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aActresseszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aFeminism and theaterzUnited States. 0aWomen in the theaterzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomen in the theaterzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Theater / History & Criticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674037663423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674037663.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK